The Central Rift PSV Transporters Cooperative Society Limited filed the suit on December 15, 2020, seeking to stop the collection after they were relocated out of the town’s central business district.
But Justice Matheka, in her ruling, noted that the court had not been informed of an existing similar suit in another court by the time she was issuing the orders.





“It has come to my attention, through a communication by the deputy registrar, that there is a similar matter before Justice Joel Ngugi pending judgment. This fact was not disclosed to me, otherwise I would not have issued the orders,” noted Justice Matheka.
Monthly revenue
Following the orders, the county risked losing about Sh17 million monthly in revenue.
The judge referred the matter to Justice Ngugi before whom a similar one has been placed.
In their application, the matatu operators have argued that their relocation from Nakuru CBD has caused them loss of earnings, yet the county is still demanding the seasonal ticket fees from them.
Through their lawyer, Mr David Mongeri, the operators termed the move by the county unconstitutional and an unfair act that infringes on the right to fair administrative actions, saying the new grounds are unsafe and lack proper sanitation.



